'''Ōmiya Shrine''' (おおみやじんじゃ) is a {{jalink|Shinto shrine|Q845945}} located in Kamishiraiwa, {{jalink|Izu City|Q696840}}, {{jalink|Shizuoka Prefecture|Q131320}}.

It is the central shrine of the Shiraiwa district, which roughly corresponds to the former {{jalink|Shimoōmi Village|Q11360758}}<ref name="tennen">[http://www.city.izu.shizuoka.jp/gyousei/gyousei_detail000109.html City-Designated Natural Monument] - Izu City</ref>.

=== Overview ===
Many old {{jalink|munafuda|Q8008834}} (ridge plaques) are preserved, the oldest of which is inscribed with the 3rd year of {{jalink|Kōan|Q389180}} (1280) in the {{jalink|Kamakura period|Q236205}}<ref name="tennen"/><ref name="yuisho">Shrine grounds history inscription</ref>.

Because the nearby {{jalink|Kamishiraiwa Site}} dates back to the {{jalink|Jōmon period|Q52824}}, and because there is also a place name “Motomura” in the area, it is considered the oldest shrine established earliest in the surrounding region<ref name="tennen"/><ref name="yuisho"/>.

Before the Edo period, it was called '''Shiraiwa Ōasa Shrine''' (しらいわ おおあさじんじゃ), and together with {{jalink|Yōhara Shrine#Related Shrines|Q11541065|Ōasa Shrine}} in Shimo Kanuki, {{jalink|Numazu City|Q241037}}, it is listed as a candidate for “Ōasa Shrine” in the {{jalink|List of Shikinaisha Shrines of Izu Province|Q11380552|Shikinaisha}}<ref name="yuisho"/>. (In the nearby southeastern district (Yahata district), there is also {{jalink|Kinomiya Shrine (Yahata, Izu City)|Q119929624|Kinomiya Shrine}}, which is a candidate for another Shikinaisha, “Sugihokowake-no-Mikoto Shrine.”)

The {{jalink|shrine forest}} surrounding the shrine buildings is designated as a city natural monument<ref name="tennen"/>.

=== Enshrined Deity ===
* {{jalink|Ōnamuchi-no-Mikoto}} ({{jalink|Ōkuninushi-no-Kami}})

=== Subsidiary Shrines within the Grounds ===
* Kinomiya Shrine  
* Hachiman Shrine  
* Yama Shrine  
* Kumano Shrine  
* Uba Shrine  
* Suwa Shrine  
* Suijin Shrine  
* Kotohira Shrine  
* Inari Shrine  

=== Cultural Properties ===
* The {{jalink|shrine forest}} of Ōmiya Shrine (City-designated Natural Monument<ref name="tennen"/>)

=== Festivals ===
* Grand Annual Festival (around October 18)

=== Access ===
* {{jalink|Tokai Bus|Q11527778}} (city-commissioned independent operation<ref>[https://www.at-s.com/news/article/shizuoka/932289.html Route Bus Nakaizu Line to Be Independently Operated by Izu City] - Shizuoka Shimbun 2021/7/21</ref>): 2 minutes on foot northeast from the “Kamishiraiwa” bus stop.

